No competent court would ever rule that package installation
scripts are copyright protected or copyright protectable.
If there just one type of software other then Hello World
in the world that this not original enough for copyright
protections it is instructions on how to install a program.

But just to be on the safe side Spike scrolls are licensed
under the GNU All Permissive License, which gives you the
same rights as if it was public domain, except (and this
is the differences from WTFPL) it all derivatives must have*
the same license so that they too are treated as public
domain.


* That is not technically what it says, but anypony that
  is not about to argue on semantics will agree with that
  interpretation.

